{
  "id": "number_methods",
  "title": "JS Number Methods",
  "group": "JS Numbers",
  "content": [
    { "type": "h1", "text": "JavaScript Number Methods" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "JavaScript provides built-in methods to work with numbers. These methods can convert numbers to strings, format decimal places, parse strings into numbers, and validate number types." },

    { "type": "h2", "text": "toString() and valueOf()" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "toString() converts a number to a string. You can optionally pass a radix (base) for different number systems. valueOf() returns the primitive value of a Number object." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "toString() and valueOf()", "code": [
      "let num = 255;",
      "",
      "// Convert to string",
      "console.log(num.toString());",
      "console.log(typeof num.toString());",
      "",
      "// Different bases (radix)",
      "console.log(num.toString(2));",
      "console.log(num.toString(8));",
      "console.log(num.toString(16));",
      "",
      "// valueOf() returns primitive number",
      "let numObj = new Number(42);",
      "console.log(numObj.valueOf());",
      "console.log(typeof numObj.valueOf());"
    ]},

    { "type": "h2", "text": "toFixed() and toPrecision()" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "toFixed() formats a number to a specified number of decimal places. toPrecision() formats a number to a specified total number of significant digits. Both return strings." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "Formatting Numbers", "code": [
      "let price = 9.6789;",
      "",
      "// toFixed(decimals) — fixed decimal places",
      "console.log(price.toFixed(0));",
      "console.log(price.toFixed(2));",
      "console.log(price.toFixed(4));",
      "",
      "let pi = 3.14159265;",
      "",
      "// toPrecision(digits) — total significant digits",
      "console.log(pi.toPrecision(2));",
      "console.log(pi.toPrecision(4));",
      "console.log(pi.toPrecision(7));",
      "",
      "// Useful for currency",
      "let total = 19.1;",
      "console.log(`$${total.toFixed(2)}`);"
    ]},

    { "type": "h2", "text": "Number(), parseInt(), parseFloat()" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "These global functions convert other types to numbers. Number() converts the entire value, parseInt() extracts an integer from the beginning of a string, and parseFloat() extracts a floating-point number." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "Converting to Numbers", "code": [
      "// Number() — converts the entire value",
      "console.log(Number(\"123\"));",
      "console.log(Number(\"123.45\"));",
      "console.log(Number(\"  99  \"));",
      "console.log(Number(\"12abc\"));",
      "console.log(Number(true));",
      "console.log(Number(false));",
      "console.log(Number(\"\"));",
      "",
      "// parseInt() — extracts integer from start",
      "console.log(parseInt(\"42px\"));",
      "console.log(parseInt(\"3.14\"));",
      "console.log(parseInt(\"0xFF\", 16));",
      "console.log(parseInt(\"11\", 2));",
      "",
      "// parseFloat() — extracts decimal from start",
      "console.log(parseFloat(\"3.14rem\"));",
      "console.log(parseFloat(\"  42.5  \"));",
      "console.log(parseFloat(\"abc\"));"
    ]},

    { "type": "h2", "text": "Number.isInteger(), Number.isFinite(), Number.isNaN()" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "These static methods on the Number object provide reliable type checking for numbers. Unlike the global isNaN() and isFinite(), these do not coerce the argument to a number first." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "Number Validation Methods", "code": [
      "// Number.isInteger()",
      "console.log(Number.isInteger(42));",
      "console.log(Number.isInteger(42.0));",
      "console.log(Number.isInteger(42.5));",
      "console.log(Number.isInteger(\"42\"));",
      "",
      "// Number.isFinite()",
      "console.log(Number.isFinite(100));",
      "console.log(Number.isFinite(Infinity));",
      "console.log(Number.isFinite(-Infinity));",
      "console.log(Number.isFinite(NaN));",
      "console.log(Number.isFinite(\"100\"));",
      "",
      "// Number.isNaN() vs global isNaN()",
      "console.log(Number.isNaN(NaN));",
      "console.log(Number.isNaN(\"hello\"));",
      "console.log(isNaN(\"hello\"));",
      "console.log(Number.isNaN(undefined));"
    ]},

    { "type": "h2", "text": "Global isNaN() vs Number.isNaN()" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "The global isNaN() first coerces its argument to a number, then checks if it is NaN. Number.isNaN() does not coerce — it only returns true if the value is exactly NaN. Always prefer Number.isNaN() for reliable checks." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "isNaN Comparison", "code": [
      "// Global isNaN() coerces first",
      "console.log(isNaN(\"hello\"));",
      "console.log(isNaN(undefined));",
      "console.log(isNaN({}));",
      "",
      "// Number.isNaN() does NOT coerce",
      "console.log(Number.isNaN(\"hello\"));",
      "console.log(Number.isNaN(undefined));",
      "console.log(Number.isNaN(NaN));",
      "",
      "// Practical example",
      "let result = 0 / 0;",
      "console.log(Number.isNaN(result));"
    ]},

    { "type": "table", "rows": [
      ["Method", "Description", "Returns"],
      ["toString(base)", "Convert to string in given base", "String"],
      ["toFixed(n)", "Format with n decimal places", "String"],
      ["toPrecision(n)", "Format with n significant digits", "String"],
      ["valueOf()", "Get primitive number value", "Number"],
      ["Number(val)", "Convert value to number", "Number"],
      ["parseInt(str, base)", "Parse integer from string", "Number"],
      ["parseFloat(str)", "Parse float from string", "Number"],
      ["Number.isInteger(val)", "Check if value is an integer", "Boolean"],
      ["Number.isFinite(val)", "Check if value is finite", "Boolean"],
      ["Number.isNaN(val)", "Check if value is exactly NaN", "Boolean"]
    ]},

    { "type": "note", "text": "Always use Number.isNaN() instead of the global isNaN(). The global version coerces its argument, so isNaN('hello') returns true even though 'hello' is not NaN — it's a string." },

    { "type": "exercise", "question": "What does parseInt('42px') return?", "options": ["NaN", "42", "'42'", "undefined"], "answer": 1 }
  ]
}
